The presidential pair planned a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its peak with the ceremony where Obama takes the prestige award.
He receives this as the fourth president of the United States, but only as the third who receives the prize directly in office.
The White House has already warned that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when he takes over the prize.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he knows that he is taking over the prize as a president currently waging war in two countries.
He intensified his war efforts a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gol medal, diploma and cheque of ten million Swedish krones (about 24 million Czech krones).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event program then provides for a banquet with the president and his wife, at which, besides the king and queen of Norway, the prime minister and 250 other invited guests will also be present.
Obama was very reluctant to the price from the beginning.
He said, for example, that he felt that he didn’t earn the prize entirely.
He also repeated several times that the price is not just for him, but for all who seek the same values as he.
Immediately after the announcement, he pointed out that for him this is "invitation to act".
