Czech discovery: a substance that also acts on HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that are already resistant to medications.
This fact prevails against the disadvantage that the compound does not work as strongly on usual virus variants as one of the medicines already existing.
The AIDS disease cannot be cured yet.
However, patients can prolong their life and prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a whole range of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus propagation also leads to the development of resistant viruses, against which no longer drugs are effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the CR Academy of Sciences, the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens up the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances referred to as metalocarborans act on the protein that is responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
The metalocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus propagation in other ways than all medicines used today, which is why they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new "improved" compounds, which have been prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages consisting of bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Home-based and resistant virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus split caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would be created.
When we turn off HIV protease, we also turn off the propagation of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press report issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the CR Academy of Sciences.
In the paper published in the journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe entire series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further changed.
