Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted for a construction ban on minarets and concerns about the alleged Islamization of Europe were widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, wrote a well-founded and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of Europe’s most explicitly secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French don't love headscarves" (original title: "Why the French don't like headscarves") (2006), an elegant and densely arguing study of a dispute issue that the country shared and occupied over a decade and a half and its impact can still be perceived today.
Bowen’s latest book offers a wider and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is actually happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes, which now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls "Islamic Free Spaces."
He is a good listener, he debates between teachers and students about the questions that worry them most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and gay rights?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-oriented banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane affairs, he claims, that make up everyday life, quite in contrast to the political dramas that the media occupy.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open up the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other hand in a modern secular society.
They don’t have all arguments on their side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists interviewed by Bowen are mostly at odds with their Salafi opposites – advocates of the purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia – which now shows a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French policymakers (and the intellectual elite, which so passionately guards the separation of church and state) feel truly committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment as Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who in turn had to make their historical compromise with secular Republicanism.
He recognizes a "sharpening of value screws" rather than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, you are inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
