Admiral Nelson’s encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old flagman to the sea who fought only with the rifle piston of his muskets is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught as they swim behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears in a performance.
Even today, zoos still typically possess one millionth of the area of life of a wild old animal. The climate is rarely suitable: the polar bear in Singapore has become quite green from the algae growing in the hollow hair of its fur.
