Ellis refers to the reports of other writers and historians and often returns to the threat that hunters pose for the survival of the species.
Although prohibited in Norway, America and Russia, killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and motor-slide-driving Inuit use powerful storm rifles to put their prey on track.
Ironically, the ice will remain the longest in the waters in the north of these two hunting nations.
In his new book "After the Ice", Alun Anderson, a former publisher of the science magazine "New Scientist", offers a clear and disturbing description of the science of the Arctic and a captivating insight into how the future could evolve.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of change.
This is not due to a lack of explanation attempts.
Fridtjof Nansen’s pioneering journeys at the end of the 19th and early 20th centuries suggested for the first time the whirlwind of the pack ice.
Underwater boats measure the shifting ridges during the Cold War.
A useful addition are satellite measurements and the large-scale application of measuring probes on icebergs, but still much is achieved by fearless people camping outside in the cold.
Anderson takes a look at the peculiar, tiny world of the flow system within the Arctic ice, formed by salt water canals compressed during freezing.
But, starting from the bear on the ice to the microscopic little miracles in the ice, all are threatened when the summer ice once passes, which is expected in the period between 2013 and 2050.
"In a few months, that could be us."
Marine soldiers were among the 6,000 who deposited crowns in Arlington.
De'Angello Robinson traveled seven hours by bus to lay a single crown on the tomb of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other marine soldiers who took the trip from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina, to the National Cemetery in Arlington to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they have walked.
In a few months, wherever we are brought back from, we could be," Robinson said about the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I wish someone would do the same for me, so I try to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who had gathered on Saturday morning to lay crowns on the tombs of veterans in several sections of the Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, founded this tradition in 1992 when he and a few others decided to decorate several hundred graves at the Arlington Cemetery.
It is now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife Karen, who make this journey every year, stop in various cities along the way to carry out events dedicated to the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America, which has also extended the event to other states.
This year, volunteers laid more than 16,000 crowns on tombs at the Arlington Cemetery, in areas of the Pentagon, on tombs at the Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at the Battery Park in New York, and at the United Airlines Flight 93 Memorial in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
The Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 for the purchase and transport of the crowns for the second time.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said, this is her way to return something to those who brought victims.
She said that is a small contribution to how we can support civilians our soldiers.
It is like visiting a family tomb.
Packed in layers of warm clothes, the volunteers wandered across the extensive lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers had older tombs from the First and Second World War and the Vietnam War as their target, as they are not visited as often as the recent tombs, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children played, and couples held their hands while carrying the fresh pine branches to the graying tombstones.
Each round crown was dark green with a small red loop attached to the upper part.
Section 60, which is located nearby and where mainly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost quiet.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 crowns to decorate this section, but the dark mood of the current wars fulfilled this area.
Individuals cryed openly, others prayed, and families and friends clinged to each other in the icy air.
Some read the names carved in stone, while others bowed down to small black-and-white square cards that had been put into the damp mud for those whose tombstones were not finished.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who shed bitter tears in front of her son’s grave.
She drove 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio to visit the tomb of Marine Infantry Deputy Officer David Shane Spicer, who fell in battle in July.
No one should ever forget why we are free... my son paid for it, she said.
“If I’ve been away for a long time, I want someone to remember him.”
U.S. government contractors arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a U.S. government contractor selling mobile phones and notebooks in the country, Foreign Ministry officials said on Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, is working for Development Alternatives Inc. based in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for customers such as USAID, the U.S. International Development Authority and for the World Bank.
Consular officials of the U.S. Interest Office in Havana are trying to gain access to the prisoner who was arrested on December 5.
The special charges have not yet been released, although Cuban law permits a Cuban citizen or foreign visitor to be arrested for almost anything accused of “danger.”
All so-called counter-revolutionary activities, including light protests and critical writings, pose a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered a serious crime.
Cuba has a growing blogger community led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who often describes how she and her husband are persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly requested permission to leave the country to receive prizes, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor will likely increase tensions between the Castro brother’s communist administration in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a “slow” approach to improve relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported by the New York Times on Friday night.
The new U.S. policy emphasizes that the United States will make a return if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as the release of political prisoners and the creation of more space for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and coveted products in a country where the average earning of a government employee is $15 a month.
The Cuban government has only allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, and it is used to send text messages, as a 15-minute phone call would cost a daily salary.
Internet usage is extremely restricted on the island.
It is accessible in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government agencies, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Many websites have limited access.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens in prison in Cuba are sitting behind grids for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press spokeswoman for the U.S. representation of interest in Havana.
Berbena said she couldn't give any further information about the arrest.
The arrest and imprisonment are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the delivery of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the group "Human Rights Watch", who recently released a tough report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, the same brother of Cuba", replacing the sickness of Raul Castro, the leader of the country.
Vivanco said the defendants would be arrested, convicted and imprisoned very often within a day.
He said that any solution would probably be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, precisely at the time the two countries are moving towards more dialogue.
Pakistani government officials uncover plan to send men to Afghanistan
Pakistani authorities on Saturday discovered an alleged leader in a conspiracy aimed at sending five men from North Virginia to Afghanistan to kill U.S. soldiers, saying they hope this case could help uncover an extensive network of terrorist recruiters searching for radicalized young men on the Internet.
Investigators said they had been looking for an opaque rebel, known as Saifullah, who had invited the men to Pakistan after finding them because one of them had commented on terrorist attacks on the YouTube video site.
Upon their arrival in Pakistan, Saifullah became the leader of these men and tried to help them reach the remote territory in Pakistan’s tribal belt, which is the home of Al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a representative of Pakistan’s intelligence agency, who was informed of the matter, said Saturday Saifullah could not convince Al Qaeda leaders that the men were not part of a CIA conspiracy to undermine the terrorist network.
As a result, they were held for days in the eastern town of Sargodha, far away from the unhosted mountains in the northwest, which have become a terrorist refuge.
They were seen as part of a covert operation.
That is why they were rejected, the government official said, who wanted to remain anonymous due to the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said the men were by no means discouraged and continued to try to obtain the right recommendations to get access to Al Qaeda camps when they were arrested by Pakistani law enforcement agencies.
The case of the five men – who remain in Pakistan and are being questioned by the FBI – underlines the critical role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and possibly even more importantly in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the September 11, 2001 attacks, the U.S. intelligence agency has made it a matter of utmost urgency to house human assets within Al Qaeda.
The recruiters of the organization act as porters who do not let in those whose commitment to the Holy War is not serious enough and those who could be spies.
American recruits are undergoing a special examination by A Qaeda, analysts said.
Due to their potential access to U.S. targets and their propaganda value, they are also considered to be tremendously attractive to the group.
Evan Kohlmann, the top analyst of the NEFA foundation based in the U.S., said terrorist groups have also become much more cautious over the past few years when it comes to whom they will allow access, as U.S. intelligence agencies have become experts on their recruitment methods.
“If you try to bring someone into these groups, what better way could you go than to follow the recruitment model that so many have already followed,” Kohlmann said.
The model is now much more based on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of protesters demand climate action in Copenhagen
Tens of thousands of protesters marched here through the streets on Saturday, calling for bolder action in climate protection from the negotiators at the city’s Bella congress centre.
Demonstrators said 100,000 people had joined the event, while police estimates were more likely to be about 25,000.
The event went relatively peacefully, although a handful of masked activists ignited small explosives near some government buildings in downtown.
On one day, when the UN-supported climate negotiations had little happened, thousands of activists with transparents wandered through the city, on which it was written in English “There is no Planet B” and one in Spanish that declared “The Earth says “enough.”
Some stars joined the protest, for example the Danish model, photographer Helena Christensen, who said that traveling to Peru, her mother’s homeland, makes her aware of the heartbreaking problems the country has to face due to the already noticeable impacts of climate change.
That’s part of the reasons why I decided to take part in the big demonstration – to spread the word and appeal to the world leaders to reach a fair, ambitious and binding agreement.
It’s not an easy task, but it has to be done now and there’s no way around it anymore.
Police stopped the protesters from getting too close to the Bella Center, saying they had arrested 19 people, mainly because they were either masked or carrying pocket knives.
According to Danish law, these actions are prohibited during demonstrations.
According to one spectator who did not want to be named because he was involved in the climate negotiations, masked demonstrators in black clothing lit several explosives near the main Copenhagen Channel, near which several ministries are located.
They threw them near the buildings, he said, adding that they started as light rockets, but were then followed by "a few major explosions."
Inside the congress centre, people gathered in front of television screens to watch the demonstration throughout the afternoon.
But the protest has apparently not reached the awareness of major officials, such as Su Wie, China’s chief climate negotiator.
When asked if he thinks the demonstration would have a constructive effect on international considerations, he replied in English: "This is something I was not aware of."
He then went on in Mandarin and said, "Because the venue is big, I can't hear what's going on outside."
He noted that it depends on the perspective of the individual whether the demonstration would harm or help.
It shows the focus of the general public and various sectors on the issue of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, “one can also say that they disrupt the negotiations or the freedom of other people.”
Examination data shows persistent race gap
The mathematical performance testimony was last week welcome good news for public schools in Washington D.C.
Although the Washington District is still far behind the country’s high-performance schools, evidence shows that fourth and eighth graders have made faster progress over the past two years than cities that include Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what is included in the latest figures of the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) is the persistent performance gap between African-American and white students, both locally and nationally.
The average score of white fourth graders from Washington D.C. rose from 262 to 270 in the last two years (on a scale of 500), but their African American peers rose only by three points from 209 to 212.
The performance gap actually increased from 53 points to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of the African American eighth graders remained basically the same, falling by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white students was not included in the test data because the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not more encouraging.
The gap that separated white and black fourth graders in 2003 when the first NAEP was recorded in this district was 60 scale points (262 to 202).
And although the score that children of both groups have reached has grown over this period of time, the difference has barely decreased with 58 points now.
Some proponents of the district’s education expressed concern last week that the results celebrated by Chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and Democratic Mayor Adrian M. Fenty were driven for the most part by white students who are already powerful children anyway.
This suggests that we have raised the overall rating by treating those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and difficult, said Jeff Smith, board member of D.C. Voice, a non-profit group advocating for educational equality in Washington, D.C..
I do not jump up and down for a two- or three-point range, said Washington Democratic City Council member Kwame R. Brown, who has a daughter in the fourth grade of Eaton Elementary School.
Brown, a common critic of Rhee’s management style, said the message of the exam scores is that the city’s middle schools urgently need attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, which I respect.
What scares me, however, is that we don’t spend nearly the time and energy that we should spend on our middle school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of poor students.
This autumn, for example, some teachers will be trained to use a new reading program, the Wilson Reading System, aimed at students in the upper grades of primary and secondary school, which did not master basic reading skills at the beginning of their school career and which lag significantly behind their same age classmates.
Everyday Mathematics, a curriculum that focuses on games and real-life experiences from kindergarten to sixth grade, was brought to Washington under former senior school inspector Clifford Janey and attributed to this curriculum some of the NAEP progress reported last week.
I think we have to continue to work on making the best measures benefit students who are below the grade level, Rhee said.
Others say that the NAEP results highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the extra money and resources for poor schools that are needed to reduce the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a professor of education at the University of California in Berkeley, who examines urban examination results.
The conventional remedy is to direct its resources and management reforms to the schools located in the poorest areas of Washington D.C..
The objective could have political consequences that work against this important agenda item.
The weak point, of course, as with other urban school inspectors, is that she is trying to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to make sure we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our schools in the neighborhoods so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive excellent public education.
Janey, now a school inspector in Newark, said in an interview this week that one of the most important elements to close the power gap is to extend the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with charter schools.
One must increase the school year to nearly 200 days in order to have the power to change, said Janey, who reached an agreement with his teacher union last year on 185 days a year, which he sees as “a milestone” on the way to a greater increase in the next contract.
Higher education for more people than prospects for the future
The coach reaches Gettysburg College with a loud whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, climbs out and blinks for a moment at the sight of the white columns, brick façades and emerald green lawn.
Graciela’s parents barely completed high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was recovered in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never set a foot on a college campus.
Their attitude and that of the other eighth graders of the group exploring Gettysburg, where lessons cost $38,690 a year, was more that of an honorable visitor than that of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes, I'll be here soon!" cried Graciela, who likes to study medicine, when the Führer announced that they had now entered the building for natural sciences.
"Wow, really?" she thoughtfully said when she was reported on the school's low professor-to-student ratio.
The College in Pennsylvania was the seventh that the children attended on their three-day tour and now they have fully accepted the intended message: the question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is a growing concern about the large number of children of Hispanic immigrants born in the United States who do not finish high school or become pregnant as a teenager, but on the other hand, there are hundreds of thousands who receive the college training necessary to rise to the middle class.
In fact, one in five of these "second generations" of Hispanic Americans is completing college – which is a remarkable achievement as many of their immigrant parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the United States without completing high school.
Their success stories are important, say researchers, because they show the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country’s workforce.
Those who study powerful children say they often have a natural affinity for school and an inherent drive for success.
Many of them also have parents who set their children high goals and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counselling programs also play a big role in helping Graciela and millions of children like her get to college, especially if these efforts persist for a long time.
If you look at low-income children whose parents do not have the experience and skills to help them find their way through the system, then a single measure at some point will not solve the problem, said Patricia Gándara, a researcher at the University of California in Davis, who studied Hispano-American students.
We need to think about providing a supportive network for these children from preschool to high school.
The federal program that was funded by Graciela’s college tour is a useful example.
It is known as GEAR UP - One Gear Up - and provides more than $300 million a year for local school systems to launch college preparation programs that begin when low-income students are in middle school and continue until they have finished high school.
According to the U.S. Department of Education, the program has helped more than 10 million students since 1999, more than 60% of whom have gone to college.
Iraqi oil ministry signs contracts with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has been able to cause larger oil companies to rebuild its damaged infrastructure at two auctions concluded on Saturday.
The ten contracts concluded with foreign oil companies by the Iraqi oil ministry suggest that China, Russia and European oil companies are willing to play an important role in the renovation of the Iraqi oil industry, which has been paralyzed by war and economic sanctions for decades.
American companies were only able to account for shares in two of the 10 auctioned fields.
Seven American companies had paid for participating in the second auction, which began on Friday.
The only company that issued a bid has drawn the shorter bid.
Two American companies were able to conclude contracts for auctioned fields in June.
The thin-seeded representatives of American oil multiples at the opening of the Iraqi oil industry surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors after six years of war and instead of US companies, Asians and Europeans are paving the way, said Ruba Husari, the editor of Iraq Oil Forum, an online news service.
There will be no further offers in Iraq for a long time.
Security concerns that were still underlined by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday and political instability due to the U.S. military’s withdrawal have likely prevented American oil companies from engaging more in Iraq, which has the world’s third-largest proven crude oil reserves.
In some cases, U.S. companies were disadvantaged because competitors, especially Chinese and other state-controlled energy companies, have significantly lower wage costs and are more likely to take risks because they do not have to account for shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies to enter into contracts with the Ministry.
Larger U.S. companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, who maintain close ties with the Iraqi oil ministry and have been assisted with technical advice in recent years, have gone out of the way.
