Change of course in ageing China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters giving them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "One baby more means one grave more."
They learned these lessons so well that, as government officials in Shanghai who suddenly started changing the course due to the low birth rate and the ageing population this summer, encouraging young couples to have more than one child, their answer was immediate and final: "Not at all."
We have invested all our time and energy in a child.
There is nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a HR manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has generated two generations of notoriously thick, displaced single children lovingly called "little emperors", a population crisis is rising in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 when this policy came into effect, the UN reported.
The Population Issues Department is set to rise explosively, while the number of populations aged 60 and older in 2020 is expected to rise from 16.7 percent of the population by 2050 to 31.1 percent, which is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older people accounted for nearly 22 percent of Shanghai’s reported residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, said that couples at fertile age must have babies to “help reduce the ratio of the ageing population and alleviate the shortage of labor in the future.”
"Shanghai will soon be as old -- but not as rich -- as developed countries like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Anchored in the Constitution of the country in 1978, China’s one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial provision introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Married couples who violate this policy are facing enormous fines -- up to their triple annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplaces.
Chinese officials have attributed to this policy that the critical use of national natural resources could be avoided, whereas human rights officials have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to abort.
Many couples also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government officials have gradually weakened their stance on one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule—including town residents, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husbands and wives have been single children—and in 2007, the sound of many hard slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute for Population Research at Beijing University, said government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples two children with a partner being single child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines describing in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out municipal employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and push information sheets under the doors.
She also asked for psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not very encouraging, family planning representatives said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outdoor areas of Shanghai said a boom is evident in the applications of couples who want a second child after the campaign starts, the city districts, on the other hand, do not report any change.
For example, in the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, only four to five applications per month are received.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say the expected number of births in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 despite the campaign — slightly higher than in 2009 but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai community of Caolu, said that financial considerations are likely the main reason why many people don’t want to have children anymore.
They want to give their first one the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children, and this is legally permitted.
But they, like many Chinese, only own a minor government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misrepresent the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we are being robbed of the possibility of having more than one child.
The problem is not just in politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples indicate psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the staff manager, said she just wants a child because she was also a single child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to caring for others and we don’t really want to do so.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old owned by a translation company, said it unblue.
For middle-sized parents with a double career through which the birth rate decreases, he said, it’s about being successful and you have to be selfish.
The age group of today’s 20-39-year-olds grew up seeing their parents fight during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don’t want such a life for themselves at all, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there is the space question -- "You have to rebuild your home" -- and the life plan -- "When the child is nine months old, you have to have a CV ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to reach a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group Develops Emissions Reduction Plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- has once again set a focus on Friday with the release of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrialized nations to bear the biggest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, has shown both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important progress in a negotiation that runs out of time as more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrial and large emerging markets can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of global temperature rise policymakers should be.
The process is given great flexibility, says John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to put the focus on what U.N. climate leader Yvo de Boer called “the great whole.”
It shows the ground plan of a possible agreement in which industrialized nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also boosted the talks on Friday by guaranteeing to allocate $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change – from mastering floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that determined the conversations last week.
U.S. Climate Special Officer Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, unless they are funded by industrial nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration would have a tougher line with China as a Bush administration representative not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without rising up larger emerging markets and taking action, Stern said, complaining that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern made his statement an hour after the statement by Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, saying that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or it was "highly irresponsible" from him that he said earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China master global warming.
With the future economic direction of the world’s great powers at stake, lines have opened up within industrialized nations, as well as between industrialized nations and emerging markets.
The current struggle relates equally to the rescue of individual economies, as well as to the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their corresponding commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that the great powers are struggling to find out who should bear the costs of braking greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved more aggressively to hold the countries with very high greenhouse gas taxes accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will develop a new economic dominance, says Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the impacts of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leading participants say the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The Alliance of the small island states with 43 members presented a 24-page draft treaty on early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the small island states’ offensive “exerces political pressure on the entire political process,” partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging markets such as China and India.
The talks got a new urgency as the delegates focused on the fact that most of the open questions need to be resolved before the arrival of the leaders of the government in order to reach an agreement.
High-level representatives, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, disembarked from their planes and rushed through the Bella Center’s corridors to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to pick up claims that will be negotiated over the next week.
The pure scale of the assembly -- 13,000 people go in and out daily at the congress centre, guitar-playing activists host nightly shows in which they make fun of the countries they think are betraying and selling, and contract drafts are hand-to-hand rather than by e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just growing: almost all the major ministers are here now and from Wednesday on they will be 60 leaders in Copenhagen.
We are coming to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavy weights are coming.
