The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other flesh-eating dinosaurs: the two-foot-long and 1.50-foot-long animal ran on two strong back legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would not be special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, report Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s journal Science.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window for the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began a dig on Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about dino early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare, mostly only single fragments can be found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current teaching, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
Many of the oldest fossils, however, are incomplete, which is why the allocation of these original dinos is often controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the hedgehogs split into their three main development lines: the flesh-eating theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the velociraptor, and also the birds, known as the "Langheal", the four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plants freshently.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropode.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found clues of airbags, as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropode with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also possessed airbags and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the hedgehogs first appeared there.
Accordingly, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America across all the worlds, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangea.
For this, the fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot be derived from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
There are, of course, contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today’s Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted image could arise because in South America, many of the most primitive dino fossils have been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant land vertebrates of the Earth’s Middle Ages is still mysterious.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying-saurs, and with numerous other axes.
By the end of the Trias, the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the relatives at the border of the Trias to the Jura erupted.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs randomly survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite hit a group of animals that had also developed in the Trias and since then has been eating a shadow: the mammals.
