75% of working mothers have had problems at work due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of a study conducted by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women on the "Fertility and Careers of Women in Spain".
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working women see their career opportunities limited in the labour market because of their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are huge differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether or not women work and if so, what type of occupation they are exercising.
Those of them who do not carry out any other work outside the house, work only half a day or have no fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a fixed job, especially in the public sphere, are postponing the establishment of a family and maternity and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a fixed job get their first child on average only 3.7 years after moving together, a number that has risen to 4.1 years for women with fixed jobs that have taken longer to achieve this and that have only achieved their moving together and the first child much later.
In addition, the type of labour has a great impact on maternity, although less than the calendar in terms of conception readiness,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that needs to be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child, the higher the education level.
This difference can also be seen in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they only have a high school degree or a higher education, on average each were mothers with 25.1 or 32.1 for the first time.
Furthermore, depending on their level of education, there is another difference between women.
While the women with a major graduation marry before their first fixed job and have their first child, the women with a middle or high graduation do it exactly the other way around and first seek a fixed job and marry afterwards and then get their first child, Delgado notes.
