Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the anti-blocking braking system ABS and as with the stability control ESP now, the auxiliary braking systems in emergencies must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already obligatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light trucks, for the rest of the vehicles a currency period was set until the end of February 2011.
The action adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but because of their operation, these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking maneuver, which detects the system on the brake pedal on the basis of the brake strength executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even step on the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not slowed down with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels back during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents injuring pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistants.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents with personal injury could be prevented - as so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as small as possible.
