New Vehicle Review Programs
In these days of storms and accidents, not only the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are dragged into the workshops, where a reviewer has to assess the damages incurred and the cost of repair.
No single accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes.
That’s why nearly 100% of reviewers use these types of systems.
Service and application providers for accident assessment and repair collect the information they receive from manufacturers to process it afterwards and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all opinions are produced with their products.
The other two companies competing in the tool market for reviewing and reporting are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that manufacturers provide is not easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Head of Sales at Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each of whom provides the information in a different format.
Moreover, the volume of data to be processed is becoming increasing, to the point that in the last five years even more versions, variants and engines came on the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes on the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, because every single one of the thousand vehicle parts must be catalogued and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphical image that allows you to "click" on different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a highly sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information for 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the car park running on the roads, it is more than 99%.
In order to carry out the documentation work and to produce databases, Audatex has eight centres distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them has specialized in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical professionals) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every second day.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, however, depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or for calculating a car's filament or residual value.
The only company that knows about a driver who knows about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
When reviewing the products Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products AudaPlus, a standard solution to monitor accidents for reviewers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid depending on the purpose of use, i.e. for each opinion.
